				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">A Second Conversation With: Times Now Editor Arnab Goswami</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Betwa Sharma			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-05-10T06:13:43+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">May 10, 2014 2:13 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">May 10, 2014 2:13 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/12/world/asia/12-arnab-indiaink/12-arnab-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/12/world/asia/12-arnab-indiaink/12-arnab-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/05/12/world/asia/12-arnab-indiaink/12-arnab-indiaink-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002875124" width="592" height="312" alt="Narendra Modi, left, the prime ministerial candidate of the Bharatiya Janata Party, in conversation with Arnab Goswami.Â "   /><meta itemprop="height" content="312"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Narendra Modi, left, the prime ministerial candidate of the Bharatiya Janata Party, in conversation with Arnab Goswami.Â </span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy: Times Now.</span></figcaption></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/10/a-second-conversation-with-times-now-editor-arnab-goswami/" data-title="A Second Conversation With: Times Now Editor Arnab Goswami" data-description="India Ink follows up with the television journalist, known for his aggressive interviews, after his one-on-one with Narendra Modi of the Bharatiya Janata Party. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i>Arnab Goswami, editor in chief of the Times Now television channel, is the only journalist to have interviewed the two main contenders in the Indian national elections: Rahul Gandhi, vice president of the Indian National Congress party, and Narendra Modi, prime ministerial candidate of the opposition Bharatiya Janata Party.</i></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i></i><i>Mr. Goswami interviewed Mr. Modi, who is also the chief minister of Gujarat, at Mr. Modi&#8217;s residence in Gandhinagar, the state capital, on Thursday morning. The interview aired in India the same evening.Â </i></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><i></i><i>India InkÂ <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/01/29/a-conversation-with-times-now-editor-in-chief-arnab-goswami/">spoke to Mr. Goswami after his interview with Mr. GandhiÂ in January</a>,Â which received massive public attention because Mr. Gandhi rarely gives sit-down interviews.Â On Friday, India Ink asked Mr. Goswami about how his interview with Mr. Modi compared with the one with Mr. Gandhi and his reaction to the British comedian <a href="//india.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/29/john-oliver-on-the-american-medias-india-blind-spot/">John Oliver&#8217;sÂ recent dig</a> at Mr. Goswami&#8217;s famously combative interviewing style. Â </i></p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Modi has spoken to several news organizations this election season. What did your interview bring to the table?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think we covered a lot of ground from political controversies to the B.J.P.&#8217;s relationship with allies and potential allies, foreign policy, economy. And the issues covered were as vast as one could have it in the course of a 75- to 80-minute encounter.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So what did you find interesting about what Mr. Modi said?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What I found interesting was that when all the questions were asked, all the questions were answered. I think he was ready to take on all the questions. My job is not to assess my own interview. I leave the final judgment of whether the <span id="more-75659"></span>interviews served their purpose to the audience.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You asked Mr. Modi several times whether what he and other B.J.P. leaders had said injected caste and religion into the elections. Did you think that he satisfactorily answered your questions?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My job is to ask all the questions, and I asked several questions on issues related to the polarization of the debate on caste and religion. Let the viewers and the audience judge whether the answers were satisfactory or not.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You interviewed Rahul Gandhi earlier in this election season and now Narendra Modi. How were these interviews different?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The context of the Rahul Gandhi interview and the Narendra Modi interview were different. Rahul Gandhi was giving his first interview toward the beginning of the campaign. Narendra Modi was giving perhaps his last detailed interview at the end of the campaign.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The question for me in the case to Rahul Gandhi was &#8220;where should I start?&#8221; because it was his first-ever detailed media interview. For me, the questions in the case of Narendra Modi were that I have so much ground to cover because the political controversies had not real taken place when Rahul spoke to me in the third or fourth week of January. Whereas when I was speaking to Mr. Modi yesterday morning, there was so much that had happened during the course of this campaign.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You questioned Rahul Gandhi several times on whether Congress party leaders were involved in the 1984 anti-Sikh riots. It seemed that you were not as aggressive with Mr. Modi on the 2002 riots in Gujarat. Why is that?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think that is an incorrect perception of yours. I asked Mr. Modi as many questions on the Gujarat riot as I asked Rahul Gandhi on the 1984 riots. In fact, if you were to look at the interview in detail, I picked on what I had asked Rahul in my first question to Narendra Modi. I had asked Rahul Gandhi if any Congress men were involved, and in the case of Narendra Modi, I asked him, &#8220;Do you believe that any members from Sangh Parivar [a Hindu nationalist organization] or the B.J.P. were involved?&#8221; So I think the questions were as many and as direct with Mr. Modi as they were with Mr. Gandhi.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Of course, both of them responded differently. How people respond to interviews is not in the arena of the interviewer.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Were there any conditions set by by Mr. Modi&#8217;s side for giving this interview?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Those who have followed my career over the past 19 years, and those who have followed my work at Times Now, would know very well that I&#8217;m an independent journalist who never accepts any conditions from anyone on the basis of which I get interviews. So neither in the case of Narendra Modi, nor in the case of Rahul Gandhi, would I accept any red lines.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Your interview with Mr. Modi doesn&#8217;t seem to have received the same response as the one with Mr. Gandhi, which played out over days?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You are mistaken, and you can take the statistics from those on Twitter. The Narendra Modi interview was trending globally as the No. 1 trend for quite a few hours yesterday. I take that as an index of the great amount of interest in this interview, which I&#8217;m sure matches that of Mr. Gandhi&#8217;s.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What was the vibe like when you were speakingÂ with Mr. Modi? Tense or relaxed?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I think it was quite relaxed. I think I delayed Mr. Modi quite a bit because of the length of the interview. It started a little later than what we thought. It was supposed to start very early in the morning. And Mr. Modi was to go on his very famous road show to Varanasi. When the interview ended it was almost quarter to 10 in the morning, after having begun atÂ 8:20Â in the morning.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But one went with the flow. The atmosphere was fine. It was a politician talking to a journalist and a journalist speaking to a politician. It was a fairly professional encounter.</p>
<div class="q left">Q.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Recently John Oliver, a well-known British comedian on a new American TV show, took a dig at your aggressive manner of conducting interviews. Have you seen this and what&#8217;s your reaction to it?</p>
<div class="a left">A.</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I don&#8217;t know who John Oliver is.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>(This interview was condensed and lightly edited.)</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Betwa Sharma is a freelance journalist based in New Delhi. Follow her on Twitter</em><i>Â </i><a href="https://www.twitter.com/betwasharma" target="_blank">@betwasharma</a>.</p>
	</div>
